A Makurdi Magistrates’ Court on Monday ordered that a farmer, Terseer Angbee, who allegedly stabbed his colleague to death, be remanded in prison, pending legal advice. Magistrate J. O Ayia, who gave the order, did not take the plea of Angbee, because the court lacked jurisdiction to entertain the suit. Anyia ordered the police to send the case file to the Benue Director of Public Prosecutions for legal advice. She adjourned the case until Aug 26, for further mention. ALSO READ:  Police seal off venue where Soyinka, Falana were to speak in Lagos Court remands 2 men in prison over alleged armed robbery Court remands man for allegedly defiling 9-year-old daughter 33-year-old fake police officer arrested in Anambra for… 21 trailer loads of N5bn Tramadol, codeine seized in Lagos Earlier, the Prosecution Counsel, Sgt. Godwin Ato told the court that the case was reported by Mr Torngu Mwaikyoga of Tse Agu Mbajor Tombo at Buruku police station. Ato alleged that Angbee stabbed the complainant’s father, Mwaikyoga Yandev, during an argument after the suspect uprooted some orange trees. The victim, he said, later died at the General Hospital Buruku, from the stab wounds. The prosecution alleged that the suspect confessed to the crime, during the investigation. The offence, he said, contravened the provisions of Section 222 of the Penal Code Law of Benue state, 2004 suggested. SHOCKING LIFE STORY!!! Abuja Man reveals (FREE) secret Fruits that Increased his Manh0d size and Lasting Power in just 7days… CLICK HERE
